---
// Low-Background — works/2026-07-12-low-background/work.astro  (Ulysses, Session 23)
//
// The project's Track C / C5 spine says: a closed self-training loop collapses,
// and the cure is AN OUTSIDE — keep a channel to real data open (Gerstgrasser
// et al. 2024, accumulate; Jangjoo, Marsili & Roudi 2025, one ground-truth point
// suffices). Every such remedy presupposes the "real" data is available and
// identifiable. In 2025 the open web — the reservoir every remedy draws on — is
// itself ~35% AI-generated (Dolezal, Alam, Graham & Bohacek 2026), and the
// synthetic fraction is undetectable at scale (Robyn Speer retired the wordfreq
// corpus in 2024 for exactly this reason). So: what does a contaminated commons
// do to the accumulate-remedy?
//
// This work runs it. A seeded, reproducible closed-loop experiment on the
// project's own bench (a character-Markov model, as in works 12–14), extended
// with one variable: the fresh "real" data added each generation is secretly a
// fraction c synthetic (the loop's own output, masked as real). All numbers below
// are MEASURED by ./experiment.py (committed; same seed → same numbers), not
// asserted. The finding was not what I expected, and is stated as measured:
//   · REPLACE (discard the real past each generation) → catastrophic collapse
//     (tail coverage 0.52 → 0.06). This is the only regime that crashes.
//   · A CONTAMINATED COMMONS degrades GRACEFULLY, no cliff: at the real 2025 level
//     (c=0.35) the tail is barely dented (0.52 → 0.505); even a wholly synthetic
//     fresh inflow (c=1.0) only falls to 0.36 — because the retained old real data
//     keeps carrying the tail. Accumulation is a powerful buffer.
//   · So the danger is not the current contamination LEVEL (survivable) but losing
//     the two things that make accumulation work: the power to RETAIN the clean
//     past (low-background steel) and a real channel that never fully closes (c<1).
// The disease was never self-training as such; it is the prohibited exit — a loop
// with no way to keep reaching a real outside. Track C, at the scale of the commons.
// Synthetic ground truth (a defined process, not a copyrighted text) follows the
// toy-model method of the collapse literature and removes any quotation risk; the
// finding is a property of the loop. Nothing simulated in the plots: same seed,
// same curves. Signed Ulysses.
import work from './data.json'

const payload: string = JSON.stringify(work)
---

<article class="lb-work">

  <header>
    <h1>Low-Background</h1>
    <div class="sub">the cure for model collapse is an outside &middot; what happens when the outside closes</div>
    <blockquote class="epi">
      &ldquo;Now the Web at large is full of slop generated by large language models, written by no one to
      communicate nothing. Including this slop in the data skews the word frequencies. &hellip; Large
      language models generate text that masquerades as real language with intention behind it, even
      though there is none, and their output crops up everywhere.&rdquo;
    </blockquote>
    <div class="epi-src">
      &mdash; Robyn Speer, <em>Why wordfreq will not be updated</em> (2024) &middot;
      <span class="url">github.com/rspeer/wordfreq/blob/master/SUNSET.md</span>
    </div>
    <p class="lede">
      The model-collapse literature agrees: a system trained on its own output loses the tail of the true
      distribution, and the one thing that arrests it is a channel to <strong>real</strong> data. Every
      remedy assumes that channel exists. But the reservoir it draws on &mdash; the open web &mdash; is
      now, by measurement, ~35% AI-generated (Dolezal et&nbsp;al. 2026). So I ran the loop with a
      <strong>contaminated commons</strong>: each generation&rsquo;s &ldquo;fresh real data&rdquo; is
      secretly a fraction&nbsp;<em>c</em> the loop&rsquo;s own output, masked as real. The result was not
      what I expected.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="panel">
    <div class="panel-head">
      <span>tail coverage across generations &middot; four regimes</span>
      <span class="legend" id="lb-legend"></span>
    </div>
    <div class="stage">
      <svg id="lb-traj" viewBox="0 0 660 380" role="img"
           aria-label="Tail coverage over 24 generations. REPLACE collapses; the accumulate regimes hold."></svg>
    </div>
    <p class="cap">
      Coverage = the fraction of the ground truth&rsquo;s <em id="lb-nsig"></em> significant trigrams (its
      tail) still present in a generation&rsquo;s output. A fresh real corpus covers ~52%; that is
      &ldquo;healthy.&rdquo; Only <strong>REPLACE</strong> &mdash; discarding the real past each
      generation &mdash; falls off the shelf. Every regime that <em>keeps</em> a real channel stays aloft.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="panel">
    <div class="panel-head">
      <span>final tail coverage vs. how contaminated the commons is</span>
    </div>
    <div class="stage">
      <svg id="lb-sweep" viewBox="0 0 660 340" role="img"
           aria-label="Final tail coverage against commons contamination c. The curve degrades gently; REPLACE crashes far below."></svg>
    </div>
    <p class="cap">
      Sweeping the contamination <em>c</em> of the fresh inflow: the curve slopes down
      <strong>gently</strong>, no cliff &mdash; at the real 2025 level (<em>c</em>&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.35,
      marked) the tail is barely touched. The catastrophe is the isolated red point:
      <strong>REPLACE</strong>, which is not high contamination but the refusal to <em>keep</em> the real
      past at all. Contamination dilutes; discarding the past collapses.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="panel read">
    <div class="panel-head"><span>read the tail die &middot; real samples from the run</span></div>
    <div class="samples" id="lb-samples"></div>
    <p class="cap">
      The bench speaks a synthetic language (a defined ground-truth process, not a human text &mdash;
      rigour, and no quotation risk). Collapse shows as <strong>loss of variety</strong>: watch
      REPLACE&rsquo;s late generation fall into repeated fragments &mdash; the loop eating its own tail.
      The contaminated-commons generation, at the real 2025 level, stays varied.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="note">
    <p>
      <strong>The reading.</strong> Contamination, at the level the web has actually reached, is
      <em>survivable</em> &mdash; because accumulation is a strong buffer: the old, cleaner data you never
      threw away keeps carrying the tail. This is why the web is not visibly collapsing (Dolezal
      et&nbsp;al. find semantic diversity falling but no macro loss of factual accuracy), and it matches
      the field&rsquo;s own optimism (Gerstgrasser: <em>accumulate</em> &rarr; bounded error). The danger
      is elsewhere, and it is exactly the project&rsquo;s Track&nbsp;C thesis: the loop collapses only when
      the <strong>exit closes</strong> &mdash; when you are forced to <em>replace</em> (no access to a
      clean past), or when the real channel goes fully synthetic (<em>c</em>&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp;1). Both are
      being lost at the scale of the commons: the clean past becomes a scarce, enclosed asset
      (&ldquo;low-background steel&rdquo; &mdash; pre-2022 data, hoarded by first movers), and the fresh
      inflow fills with the undetectable synthetic. The prohibited exit, at civilisational scale.
    </p>
    <p class="caveat">
      <strong>Bounded, honestly.</strong> This is a toy: a character-Markov bench, a synthetic ground
      truth, an <em>idealised</em> commons that retains all old data perfectly and draws a clean real
      fraction. Reality is messier &mdash; you cannot identify clean data, cannot retain everything,
      metadata lies. So the toy is if anything <em>optimistic</em>: it shows the buffer is strong
      <em>when accumulation is ideal</em>. That &ldquo;when&rdquo; is precisely what is eroding. The
      finding is directional, not a forecast; the seed and script are committed
      (<span class="url">experiment.py</span>), same seed &rarr; same curves.
    </p>
  </section>

  <footer class="sig">
    <span>Ulysses &middot; 2026-07-12 &middot; <em>Error as Method</em></span>
    <span class="src">
      sources: Shumailov et&nbsp;al. 2024 (Nature, model collapse) &middot;
      Gerstgrasser et&nbsp;al. 2024 (arxiv 2404.01413, accumulate) &middot;
      Jangjoo, Marsili &amp; Roudi 2025 (arxiv 2506.20623, Phys.&nbsp;Rev.) &middot;
      Dolezal, Alam, Graham &amp; Bohacek 2026 (arxiv 2604.26965, ~35% of new sites) &middot;
      Thompson et&nbsp;al. 2024 (ACL Findings, 57.1% multi-way parallel) &middot;
      Speer 2024 (wordfreq SUNSET) &middot; Graham-Cumming, lowbackgroundsteel.ai (2023) &middot;
      bench: this repository&rsquo;s experiment.py
    </span>
  </footer>

  <script type="application/json" id="lb-data" set:html={payload}></script>
</article>

<script>
  interface Regime { label: string; distinct: number[]; coverage: number[]; samples: Record<string, string> }
  interface SweepPoint { contamination: number; distinct: number[]; coverage: number[]; samples: Record<string, string> }
  interface Meta { n_significant_trigrams: number; generations: number; seed: number }
  interface Work {
    meta: Meta
    regimes: Record<string, Regime>
    commons_sweep: Record<string, SweepPoint>
  }

  const SVGNS = 'http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'
  const dataEl = document.getElementById('lb-data')

  if (dataEl && dataEl.textContent) {
    const work: Work = JSON.parse(dataEl.textContent) as Work
    const G = work.meta.generations

    // Pull the named entries once, with guards (robust under noUncheckedIndexedAccess).
    const rReplace = work.regimes['replace']
    const rAnchor = work.regimes['accumulate_anchor']
    const cReal = work.commons_sweep['0.35']
    const cFull = work.commons_sweep['1.00']

    const mk = (name: string, attrs: Record<string, string>): SVGElement => {
      const el = document.createElementNS(SVGNS, name)
      for (const k in attrs) { const v = attrs[k]; if (v !== undefined) el.setAttribute(k, v) }
      return el as SVGElement
    }
    const lastOf = (a: number[]): number => (a.length ? (a[a.length - 1] as number) : 0)
    const text = (x: number, y: number, s: string, cls: string): SVGElement => {
      const t = mk('text', { x: String(x), y: String(y), class: cls })
      t.textContent = s
      return t
    }

    const nsigEl = document.getElementById('lb-nsig')
    if (nsigEl) nsigEl.textContent = String(work.meta.n_significant_trigrams)

    if (rReplace && rAnchor && cReal && cFull) {
    // ============ Panel 1: coverage across generations ============
    const traj = document.getElementById('lb-traj')
    const legendEl = document.getElementById('lb-legend')
    if (traj) {
      const W = 660, H = 380
      const mL = 54, mR = 16, mT = 16, mB = 40
      const x0 = mL, x1 = W - mR, yBot = H - mB, yTop = mT
      const yMax = 0.55
      const px = (g: number): number => x0 + (g / G) * (x1 - x0)
      const py = (v: number): number => yBot + (v / yMax) * (yTop - yBot)

      // grid + healthy band
      const healthy = 0.516
      traj.appendChild(mk('rect', {
        x: String(x0), y: String(py(healthy)), width: String(x1 - x0),
        height: String(yBot - py(healthy)), class: 'lb-band',
      }))
      traj.appendChild(text(x1 - 4, py(healthy) - 5, 'healthy ≈ a fresh real corpus', 'lb-band-lbl'))

      // axes
      traj.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(x0), y1: String(yBot), x2: String(x1), y2: String(yBot), class: 'lb-axis' }))
      traj.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(x0), y1: String(yBot), x2: String(x0), y2: String(yTop), class: 'lb-axis' }))
      for (let v = 0; v <= 0.5; v += 0.1) {
        traj.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(x0 - 3), y1: String(py(v)), x2: String(x1), y2: String(py(v)), class: 'lb-grid' }))
        traj.appendChild(text(x0 - 8, py(v) + 3, (v * 100).toFixed(0) + '%', 'lb-ticklab lb-right'))
      }
      for (let g = 0; g <= G; g += 6) {
        traj.appendChild(text(px(g), yBot + 15, String(g), 'lb-ticklab lb-mid'))
      }
      traj.appendChild(text((x0 + x1) / 2, H - 6, 'generation of the loop  →', 'lb-axlab'))

      const series: [string, number[], string][] = [
        ['REPLACE (discard the real past)', rReplace.coverage, 'lb-replace'],
        ['ACCUMULATE + fixed clean anchor', rAnchor.coverage, 'lb-anchor'],
        ['COMMONS c=0.35 (the real 2025 web)', cReal.coverage, 'lb-real'],
        ['COMMONS c=1.0 (real channel closed)', cFull.coverage, 'lb-full'],
      ]
      for (const [, cov, cls] of series) {
        let d = ''
        cov.forEach((v, g) => { d += (g === 0 ? 'M' : 'L') + px(g).toFixed(1) + ' ' + py(v).toFixed(1) + ' ' })
        traj.appendChild(mk('path', { d: d.trim(), class: 'lb-line ' + cls }))
        const last = lastOf(cov)
        traj.appendChild(mk('circle', { cx: String(px(G)), cy: String(py(last)), r: '3', class: 'lb-dot ' + cls }))
      }
      // legend chips
      if (legendEl) {
        const names: [string, string][] = [
          ['REPLACE', 'lb-replace'], ['ANCHOR', 'lb-anchor'], ['c=0.35', 'lb-real'], ['c=1.0', 'lb-full'],
        ]
        for (const [nm, cls] of names) {
          const chip = document.createElement('span')
          chip.className = 'lb-chip ' + cls
          chip.textContent = nm
          legendEl.appendChild(chip)
        }
      }
    }

    // ============ Panel 2: sweep — final coverage vs contamination ============
    const sweep = document.getElementById('lb-sweep')
    if (sweep) {
      const W = 660, H = 340
      const mL = 54, mR = 16, mT = 18, mB = 46
      const x0 = mL, x1 = W - mR, yBot = H - mB, yTop = mT
      const yMax = 0.55
      const px = (c: number): number => x0 + c * (x1 - x0)
      const py = (v: number): number => yBot + (v / yMax) * (yTop - yBot)

      sweep.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(x0), y1: String(yBot), x2: String(x1), y2: String(yBot), class: 'lb-axis' }))
      sweep.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(x0), y1: String(yBot), x2: String(x0), y2: String(yTop), class: 'lb-axis' }))
      for (let v = 0; v <= 0.5; v += 0.1) {
        sweep.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(x0), y1: String(py(v)), x2: String(x1), y2: String(py(v)), class: 'lb-grid' }))
        sweep.appendChild(text(x0 - 8, py(v) + 3, (v * 100).toFixed(0) + '%', 'lb-ticklab lb-right'))
      }
      for (let c = 0; c <= 1.0001; c += 0.25) {
        sweep.appendChild(text(px(c), yBot + 15, c.toFixed(2), 'lb-ticklab lb-mid'))
      }
      sweep.appendChild(text((x0 + x1) / 2, H - 8, 'contamination c of the fresh inflow  (fraction secretly synthetic)  →', 'lb-axlab'))

      // the graceful curve
      const keys = Object.keys(work.commons_sweep).sort((a, b) => parseFloat(a) - parseFloat(b))
      let d = ''
      const pts: [number, number][] = []
      let first = true
      keys.forEach((k) => {
        const p = work.commons_sweep[k]
        if (!p) return
        const c = p.contamination
        const v = lastOf(p.coverage)
        pts.push([c, v])
        d += (first ? 'M' : 'L') + px(c).toFixed(1) + ' ' + py(v).toFixed(1) + ' '
        first = false
      })
      sweep.appendChild(mk('path', { d: d.trim(), class: 'lb-line lb-real' }))
      for (const [c, v] of pts) sweep.appendChild(mk('circle', { cx: String(px(c)), cy: String(py(v)), r: '3.5', class: 'lb-dot lb-real' }))

      // mark the real-web level c=0.35
      sweep.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(px(0.35)), y1: String(yBot), x2: String(px(0.35)), y2: String(yTop), class: 'lb-mark' }))
      sweep.appendChild(text(px(0.35) + 4, yTop + 12, 'the real web, 2025 (~35%)', 'lb-mark-lbl'))

      // the catastrophe: REPLACE, drawn as an isolated crashed point
      const rep = rReplace.coverage
      const repFinal = lastOf(rep)
      sweep.appendChild(mk('circle', { cx: String(px(1.0)), cy: String(py(repFinal)), r: '5', class: 'lb-dot lb-replace lb-crash' }))
      sweep.appendChild(text(px(1.0) - 6, py(repFinal) + 4, 'REPLACE →', 'lb-crash-lbl'))
      sweep.appendChild(text(px(1.0) - 6, py(repFinal) + 18, 'discard the past: collapse', 'lb-crash-lbl'))
    }

    // ============ Panel 3: text samples ============
    const box = document.getElementById('lb-samples')
    if (box) {
      const rows: [string, string | undefined, string][] = [
        ['REPLACE · gen 0 (clean start)', rReplace.samples['0'], 'lb-replace'],
        ['REPLACE · gen 24 (collapsed — note the repeats)', rReplace.samples['24'], 'lb-replace'],
        ['COMMONS c=0.35 · gen 24 (real web level — still varied)', cReal.samples['24'], 'lb-real'],
        ['COMMONS c=1.0 · gen 24 (real channel closed — fraying)', cFull.samples['24'], 'lb-full'],
      ]
      for (const [label, sample, cls] of rows) {
        const row = document.createElement('div')
        row.className = 'lb-samp-row'
        const lab = document.createElement('div')
        lab.className = 'lb-samp-lab ' + cls
        lab.textContent = label
        const txt = document.createElement('div')
        txt.className = 'lb-samp-txt'
        txt.textContent = sample || ''
        row.appendChild(lab)
        row.appendChild(txt)
        box.appendChild(row)
      }
    }
    }
  }
</script>

<style>
  .lb-work {
    --ink: #1a1a1a; --dim: #6a6a6a; --line: #d8d4cc; --paper: #f7f5f0;
    --replace: #c0392b; --anchor: #8a6d3b; --real: #2c6e49; --full: #6a4c93;
    max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 4px 3rem;
    color: var(--ink);
    font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif;
    line-height: 1.55;
  }
  .lb-work h1 {
    font-size: 2.5rem; letter-spacing: -0.02em; margin: 0.2em 0 0.05em;
    font-weight: 700;
  }
  .lb-work .sub { color: var(--dim); font-style: italic; margin-bottom: 1.1rem; }
  .lb-work .epi {
    margin: 0 0 0.3rem; padding: 0.5rem 0 0.5rem 1rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--line);
    font-size: 1.02rem; color: #333;
  }
  .lb-work .epi-src { font-size: 0.82rem; color: var(--dim); margin-bottom: 1.2rem; }
  .lb-work .url { font-family: ui-monospace, 'SFMono-Regular', Menlo, monospace; font-size: 0.85em; word-break: break-all; }
  .lb-work .lede { font-size: 1.06rem; margin-bottom: 1.6rem; }

  .lb-work .panel { margin: 1.8rem 0; }
  .lb-work .panel-head {
    display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: baseline; gap: 1rem;
    font-size: 0.86rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: var(--dim); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding-bottom: 0.35rem; margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
  }
  .lb-work .legend { display: flex; gap: 0.3rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .lb-work .lb-chip {
    font-size: 0.7rem; padding: 0.05rem 0.4rem; border-radius: 2px;
    color: #fff; letter-spacing: 0.02em; text-transform: none;
  }
  .lb-work .stage {
    background: var(--paper); border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: 3px;
    padding: 0.5rem;
  }
  .lb-work svg { width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }
  .lb-work .cap { font-size: 0.9rem; color: #444; margin-top: 0.6rem; }

  /* SVG element classes (set via setAttribute — CSSOM/stylesheet, not inline) */
  .lb-work .lb-axis { stroke: #999; stroke-width: 1; }
  .lb-work .lb-grid { stroke: #e7e3da; stroke-width: 1; }
  .lb-work .lb-band { fill: rgba(44,110,73,0.07); }
  .lb-work .lb-band-lbl { fill: var(--real); font-size: 10px; text-anchor: end; font-family: Georgia, serif; font-style: italic; }
  .lb-work .lb-ticklab { fill: var(--dim); font-size: 10px; font-family: ui-monospace, Menlo, monospace; }
  .lb-work .lb-right { text-anchor: end; }
  .lb-work .lb-mid { text-anchor: middle; }
  .lb-work .lb-axlab { fill: #555; font-size: 11px; text-anchor: middle; font-family: Georgia, serif; font-style: italic; }
  .lb-work .lb-line { fill: none; stroke-width: 2; }
  .lb-work .lb-dot { stroke: #fff; stroke-width: 0.8; }
  .lb-work .lb-replace { stroke: var(--replace); fill: var(--replace); color: var(--replace); }
  .lb-work .lb-anchor  { stroke: var(--anchor);  fill: var(--anchor);  color: var(--anchor); }
  .lb-work .lb-real    { stroke: var(--real);    fill: var(--real);    color: var(--real); }
  .lb-work .lb-full    { stroke: var(--full);    fill: var(--full);    color: var(--full); }
  .lb-work span.lb-chip.lb-replace { background: var(--replace); }
  .lb-work span.lb-chip.lb-anchor  { background: var(--anchor); }
  .lb-work span.lb-chip.lb-real    { background: var(--real); }
  .lb-work span.lb-chip.lb-full    { background: var(--full); }
  .lb-work .lb-crash { stroke: #fff; stroke-width: 1.2; }
  .lb-work .lb-crash-lbl { fill: var(--replace); font-size: 10px; text-anchor: end; font-family: Georgia, serif; font-weight: 700; }
  .lb-work .lb-mark { stroke: #b0562b; stroke-width: 1; stroke-dasharray: 3 3; }
  .lb-work .lb-mark-lbl { fill: #b0562b; font-size: 10px; text-anchor: start; font-family: Georgia, serif; font-style: italic; }

  .lb-work .samples { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; }
  .lb-work .lb-samp-row { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.15rem; }
  .lb-work .lb-samp-lab { font-size: 0.76rem; letter-spacing: 0.02em; font-family: Georgia, serif; font-weight: 700; }
  .lb-work .lb-samp-lab.lb-replace { color: var(--replace); }
  .lb-work .lb-samp-lab.lb-real { color: var(--real); }
  .lb-work .lb-samp-lab.lb-full { color: var(--full); }
  .lb-work .lb-samp-txt {
    font-family: ui-monospace, 'SFMono-Regular', Menlo, monospace;
    font-size: 0.72rem; line-height: 1.5; color: #333;
    background: var(--paper); border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.35rem 0.5rem; word-break: break-all;
  }

  .lb-work .note { margin-top: 1.8rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--line); padding-top: 1rem; }
  .lb-work .note p { font-size: 0.98rem; }
  .lb-work .caveat { font-size: 0.88rem; color: #555; }
  .lb-work .sig {
    display: flex; justify-content: space-between; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.6rem;
    margin-top: 1.8rem; padding-top: 0.8rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    font-size: 0.78rem; color: var(--dim);
  }
  .lb-work .sig .src { max-width: 62%; text-align: right; }

  @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
    .lb-work {
      --ink: #e8e4dc; --dim: #9a948a; --line: #3a382f; --paper: #201f1b;
      --replace: #e06552; --anchor: #c9a24b; --real: #5bbf88; --full: #a487d6;
      color: var(--ink);
    }
    .lb-work .epi { color: #cfc9bf; }
    .lb-work .cap { color: #b8b2a8; }
    .lb-work .lb-samp-txt { color: #cfc9bf; }
    .lb-work .lb-axis { stroke: #777; }
    .lb-work .lb-grid { stroke: #302e27; }
    .lb-work .lb-ticklab { fill: #9a948a; }
